14
00:01:19,099 --> 00:01:20,199
Next case.

15
00:01:24,199 --> 00:01:26,999
-lt was a long time ago.
-And is he good?

16
00:01:27,199 --> 00:01:29,499
Yeah, he can really break it up!

17
00:01:29,699 --> 00:01:31,199
Billy's weird.

18
00:01:31,399 --> 00:01:32,999
He gets so tired.

19
00:01:33,199 --> 00:01:34,699
Do you like this lipstick?

20
00:01:34,999 --> 00:01:36,199
She was terrific.

21
00:01:36,399 --> 00:01:38,199
lt's 32 now and going fast.

22
00:01:38,399 --> 00:01:39,899
He can't afford to get out.

23
00:01:40,099 --> 00:01:42,399
l got a thousand shares of that.

24
00:01:43,399 --> 00:01:47,799
We have to have the AP, lateral and
1 0 units done before they can begin.

25
00:01:47,999 --> 00:01:50,699
lt says here, type and cross-match
was done yesterday.

26
00:01:50,899 --> 00:01:53,299
Just standard workup procedure.

27
00:01:53,799 --> 00:01:54,599
Well, l don't know.

28
00:01:54,799 --> 00:01:57,299
So it was a clear case of endocarditis.

29
00:01:57,499 --> 00:01:59,799
We're ready when you are,
Dr. Wheeler.

30
00:01:59,999 --> 00:02:01,299
No response to antibiotics.

31
00:02:05,698 --> 00:02:06,798
Cut her, okay?

32
00:02:06,998 --> 00:02:09,398
-Sponge.
-Begin to tie off.

33
00:02:15,498 --> 00:02:17,598
<i>It's all politics.
Today, for instance...</i>

34
00:02:17,798 --> 00:02:22,598
...Rudnick says to me, ''l hear you're
the new chief resident in surgery.''

35
00:02:22,798 --> 00:02:25,398
-That's great!
-He was testing me.

36
00:02:25,598 --> 00:02:27,698
Then he says that Harris told him...

37
00:02:27,898 --> 00:02:31,198
...that Mark Bellows was going to be
the next chief resident.

38
00:02:31,398 --> 00:02:33,598
-Wonderful, Mark.
-But here's the thing.

39
00:02:33,798 --> 00:02:37,798
He waited for me to say l knew
about it. That wouldn't look right.

40
00:02:37,998 --> 00:02:41,998
That would look as if l expected it.
So l said l hadn't heard anything.

41
00:02:42,198 --> 00:02:44,498
You've wanted it for two years.

42
00:02:44,698 --> 00:02:47,598
But there's no point
in saying that, is there?

43
00:02:47,798 --> 00:02:48,998
l said...

44
00:02:49,298 --> 00:02:51,998
...l thought it'd be wonderful
if it happened.

45
00:02:52,198 --> 00:02:55,298
l said Chandler was doing
an excellent job as chief resident.

46
00:02:55,498 --> 00:02:58,798
But l said there was a little room
left for improvement.

47
00:02:58,998 --> 00:03:00,798
Chandler's damn good.

48
00:03:01,998 --> 00:03:04,198
l really laid it on thick
with old Rudnick.

49
00:03:04,398 --> 00:03:08,997
l told him l was following his hepatic
research, cited some references.

50
00:03:09,197 --> 00:03:10,797
He was impressed.

51
00:03:10,997 --> 00:03:13,197
Procedure went well too.

52
00:03:13,397 --> 00:03:15,897
So all in all, it was a good day.

53
00:03:16,597 --> 00:03:20,197
l'm gonna take a shower.
Can you grab me a beer before dinner?

54
00:03:20,397 --> 00:03:21,697
Hey, Mark.

55
00:03:21,897 --> 00:03:22,997
Get your own beer.

56
00:03:23,397 --> 00:03:26,497
-Honey, for chrissakes, come on.
-l want to take a shower.

57
00:03:26,797 --> 00:03:28,997
-l was on call last night.
-So was l.

58
00:03:29,197 --> 00:03:30,897
l know, but l had two arrests...

59
00:03:31,097 --> 00:03:34,197
...aortic aneurysm blew at 4 a.m.,
had to be done stat.

60
00:03:34,397 --> 00:03:38,097
So l didn't get any sleep, and
l'd really like to take a shower.

61
00:03:40,397 --> 00:03:42,397
lf you don't mind.

62
00:03:42,597 --> 00:03:44,297
l had a hard day too.

63
00:03:45,597 --> 00:03:48,397
You get in the shower faster
than any person alive.

64
00:03:48,897 --> 00:03:50,897
Have a beer.
You'll feel better.

65
00:03:54,097 --> 00:03:56,497
l know what'd make me feel better.

66
00:03:56,697 --> 00:03:58,697
Goddamn doctors.

67
00:03:59,597 --> 00:04:02,097
Couldn't have fallen
in love with a nurse.

68
00:04:04,997 --> 00:04:07,197
Dorothy on the eighth floor.

69
00:04:08,097 --> 00:04:09,797
She liked me.

70
00:04:12,097 --> 00:04:14,097
My own apartment.

71
00:04:17,496 --> 00:04:18,996
Did you hear about Louis?

72
00:04:19,196 --> 00:04:20,396
What about Louis?

73
00:04:20,596 --> 00:04:23,296
They passed him up
as assistant professor.

74
00:04:23,496 --> 00:04:26,796
Guy's really paid his dues too.
Now they don't take him.

75
00:04:26,996 --> 00:04:30,096
Plus his son is waiting
for a kidney transplant.

76
00:04:30,596 --> 00:04:32,096
Did you start dinner?

77
00:04:33,696 --> 00:04:34,696
What?

78
00:04:34,996 --> 00:04:36,096
Did you start dinner?

79
00:04:36,296 --> 00:04:40,996
-Did you hear anything l said?
-lt's in the fridge. Just heat it up.

80
00:04:41,196 --> 00:04:45,396
-l was telling you about my day.
-l had a hard day too.

81
00:04:46,096 --> 00:04:48,096
Just go heat it up.

82
00:04:48,296 --> 00:04:52,096
Why is it, whenever we're about
to fight, you're always undressed?

83
00:04:52,296 --> 00:04:55,096
What's the big deal?
Just heat up the stew.

84
00:04:55,296 --> 00:04:58,096
-Why won't you help out?
-ls that the way you see it?

85
00:04:58,296 --> 00:05:00,996
l make my concessions.
You always take a shower first.

86
00:05:01,196 --> 00:05:02,096
l don't.

87
00:05:02,296 --> 00:05:04,796
You do too,
and l'm getting tired of it.

88
00:05:06,596 --> 00:05:07,596
Honey, come on.

89
00:05:07,796 --> 00:05:08,596
Don't call me honey.

90
00:05:08,796 --> 00:05:12,396
l'm trying to tell you about my day.
Something that happened.

91
00:05:12,596 --> 00:05:15,096
Your days are always the same.

92
00:05:17,096 --> 00:05:18,796
What is that supposed to mean?

93
00:05:18,996 --> 00:05:20,895
Just politics, that's all.

94
00:05:21,095 --> 00:05:24,095
Who said what to whom.
Who's rising, who's falling.

95
00:05:24,295 --> 00:05:26,895
Who's made a good move, a bad move.
Politics!

96
00:05:27,095 --> 00:05:29,995
Somebody has to be interested
in hospital politics.

97
00:05:30,195 --> 00:05:31,295
You certainly are not.

98
00:05:31,495 --> 00:05:34,695
l thought you were a surgical
resident, not a political one.

99
00:05:35,195 --> 00:05:36,895
l like politics.

100
00:05:37,095 --> 00:05:40,295
They interest me. Just because
you're always looking for--

101
00:05:40,895 --> 00:05:42,995
You want me to heat up
the dinner, is that it?

102
00:05:44,095 --> 00:05:46,295
l want some respect.

103
00:05:46,495 --> 00:05:48,895
Susan, come on.
Don't leave again.

104
00:05:49,395 --> 00:05:51,495
Why can't you share
half the responsibility?

105
00:05:51,695 --> 00:05:53,895
l share more than
half the responsibility!

106
00:05:54,095 --> 00:05:56,295
-No need to shout.
-Why are you running off?

107
00:05:56,495 --> 00:05:59,395
You think l want this?
Let me tell you something.

108
00:05:59,595 --> 00:06:02,095
l make concessions
for this so-called relationship.

109
00:06:02,295 --> 00:06:05,095
l know it's hard on you politically.

110
00:06:12,195 --> 00:06:13,195
Susan, don't go.

111
00:06:15,495 --> 00:06:17,695
You know what the trouble with you is?

112
00:06:17,895 --> 00:06:20,295
All you care about
is being chief resident.

113
00:06:20,495 --> 00:06:23,995
You know what your trouble is?
You don't want a relationship.

114
00:06:24,195 --> 00:06:26,494
Look at you.
You run away from it.

115
00:06:26,694 --> 00:06:28,294
This is ridiculous.

116
00:06:29,094 --> 00:06:30,594
You don't want a lover...

117
00:06:30,794 --> 00:06:32,794
...you want a goddamn wife!

118
00:07:14,394 --> 00:07:15,894
Bastard.

119
00:07:27,894 --> 00:07:29,694
l have a bleeder here.

120
00:07:29,894 --> 00:07:32,393
-l need more suction.
-Clamp.

121
00:07:35,993 --> 00:07:39,393
He's not di-toxic.
He has advanced ASHD.

122
00:07:41,893 --> 00:07:43,993
l just bought some at 43.

123
00:07:44,193 --> 00:07:47,693
Yeah, l hear they have management
problems. l sold at 37.

124
00:07:52,593 --> 00:07:54,093
How are you?

125
00:07:54,393 --> 00:07:56,393
l'm fine. The case went well.
No problem.

126
00:07:56,593 --> 00:07:57,893
Good.

127
00:07:59,293 --> 00:08:02,093
l'm really sorry about last night.

128
00:08:02,293 --> 00:08:03,893
So am l.

129
00:08:04,093 --> 00:08:06,793
-You want to have some lunch?
-l have class.

130
00:08:06,993 --> 00:08:09,793
You don't think this is
more important than the class?

131
00:08:09,993 --> 00:08:13,793
That class is the only time
l get out of this damn hospital.

132
00:08:13,993 --> 00:08:16,693
Can you understand that?
lt's important to me!

133
00:08:17,393 --> 00:08:18,793
You're impossible!

134
00:08:18,993 --> 00:08:21,193
Seven, eight, step!

135
00:08:23,793 --> 00:08:25,593
Back. Step.

136
00:08:26,693 --> 00:08:27,893
Out!

137
00:08:29,993 --> 00:08:33,393
One, two, down three,
up four and open.

138
00:08:34,193 --> 00:08:36,793
And one and two,
three and four.

139
00:08:37,093 --> 00:08:38,492
Stretch.

140
00:08:39,292 --> 00:08:41,092
Walk two, three, four...

141
00:08:41,292 --> 00:08:44,792
...and five and six, seven,
eight and back.

142
00:08:44,992 --> 00:08:47,892
-You gonna leave Mark?
-l don't know.

143
00:08:48,092 --> 00:08:49,292
l went home last night.

144
00:08:49,992 --> 00:08:50,992
Again?

145
00:08:52,392 --> 00:08:54,092
He's impossible.

146
00:08:54,892 --> 00:08:56,992
Did you see Dr. Richards?

147
00:08:58,992 --> 00:08:59,892
l don't know.

148
00:09:00,092 --> 00:09:04,392
Apparently you can tell by looking at
the cervix. lt's a different color.

149
00:09:04,592 --> 00:09:08,492
He did the lab tests and he says
l'm definitely 8 to 1 0 weeks pregnant.

150
00:09:08,692 --> 00:09:12,092
So Dr. Richards is doing
a D and C tomorrow.

151
00:09:12,892 --> 00:09:15,092
For menstrual irregularity.

152
00:09:17,192 --> 00:09:18,192
lt's simple, isn't it?

153
00:09:18,892 --> 00:09:20,392
Are you worried?

154
00:09:20,892 --> 00:09:24,692
l know you do this every day but, sure,
l'm worried. Who wouldn't be?

155
00:09:25,292 --> 00:09:28,392
lt'll be fine, Nancy.
lt's routine procedure.

156
00:09:35,392 --> 00:09:37,192
We're going to the lce Capades.

157
00:09:37,992 --> 00:09:38,992
lt's real crowded.

158
00:09:39,192 --> 00:09:40,192
Patient on call?

159
00:09:40,392 --> 00:09:43,992
-Coming right down, Dr. Cowans.
-The instruments are autoclaved.

160
00:09:44,192 --> 00:09:46,891
Let's teach you fellas
some anesthesiology.

161
00:09:47,091 --> 00:09:48,691
This is your standard anesthesia.

162
00:09:48,891 --> 00:09:53,391
You've got two main wall lines.
Nitrous oxide on the left and oxygen.

163
00:09:53,591 --> 00:09:55,891
We got a case today that's a D and C.

164
00:09:56,091 --> 00:09:59,391
lt's one of Dr. Richard's cases.
Actually, it's a TAB.

165
00:09:59,591 --> 00:10:04,091
That's a therapeutic abortion.
Keep it clean. lt's a married patient.

166
00:10:04,791 --> 00:10:07,191
On the cart here,
we got two manometers...

167
00:10:07,391 --> 00:10:10,591
...with flow valves here and here
to regulate gas.

168
00:10:10,791 --> 00:10:13,091
We got emergency oxygen down here...

169
00:10:13,291 --> 00:10:15,891
...which we checked and that's full.

170
00:10:16,091 --> 00:10:19,591
During surgery, we'll be recording this
and the vital signs.

171
00:10:19,791 --> 00:10:20,991
Hey, how is Bess?

172
00:10:21,191 --> 00:10:22,391
l don't know.

173
00:10:22,591 --> 00:10:23,991
ln and out.

174
00:10:25,991 --> 00:10:28,991
Boy, she has more rails
than anybody l know.

175
00:10:29,191 --> 00:10:30,491
She's seeing a shrink now.

176
00:10:30,691 --> 00:10:32,391
One, two, three, up!

177
00:10:32,591 --> 00:10:34,391
Anybody we know?

178
00:10:34,991 --> 00:10:38,491
Morning, Nancy. Remember me?
l'm Dr. Cowans.

179
00:10:40,591 --> 00:10:43,491
That's right, dear,
and you'll have a nice long sleep.

180
00:10:43,791 --> 00:10:46,991
Pre-op, she's received a 0.0 1
of Demerol and 0.4 of atropine...

181
00:10:47,191 --> 00:10:49,491
...so believe me,
she's pretty relaxed.

182
00:10:49,691 --> 00:10:54,290
l'll say she's relaxed!
Come on, Mrs. Greenly, on your back.

183
00:10:54,490 --> 00:10:55,790
That's it.

184
00:10:55,990 --> 00:10:58,590
-Gonna meet me for lunch?
-l don't know.

185
00:10:58,790 --> 00:11:00,490
l'll let you know, okay?

186
00:11:01,790 --> 00:11:03,290
l'll be in the lounge.

187
00:11:03,490 --> 00:11:06,690
Henry might be calling,
and if he does, you know....

188
00:11:06,890 --> 00:11:09,790
-Okay, no problem.
-Yeah, okay.

189
00:11:11,090 --> 00:11:13,590
-Good afternoon, Tom.
-Afternoon, Jim. How's our lady?

190
00:11:13,890 --> 00:11:14,690
Just about ready.

191
00:11:14,890 --> 00:11:16,390
l'm still awake.

192
00:11:16,590 --> 00:11:18,890
-But not for long, dear.
-You promise?

193
00:11:19,090 --> 00:11:22,190
l'll induce with sodium Pentothal,
give an lV by syringe.

194
00:11:22,390 --> 00:11:23,990
Nance, what l want you to do...

195
00:11:24,190 --> 00:11:27,890
...is start counting from 1 00
backwards real slow, okay?

196
00:11:28,390 --> 00:11:29,990
Here we go.

197
00:11:30,190 --> 00:11:33,290
-A hundred.
-Ninety-nine...

198
00:11:33,990 --> 00:11:35,790
...ninety-eight...

199
00:11:36,790 --> 00:11:38,590
...ninety-seven...

200
00:11:39,490 --> 00:11:41,190
...ninety-six....

201
00:11:43,290 --> 00:11:45,390
lt's quick. Stop the pentothal.

202
00:11:45,690 --> 00:11:47,990
You see, pentothal isn't
really an anesthetic.

203
00:11:48,190 --> 00:11:50,890
Any deep pain right now
and she'd wake right up.

204
00:11:51,090 --> 00:11:53,890
What we need for anesthesia is gas.

205
00:11:54,090 --> 00:11:56,489
First l'll inject some succinylcholine.

206
00:11:56,689 --> 00:12:00,689
l want you to watch her chest gauge
because she'll stop breathing.

207
00:12:04,289 --> 00:12:07,889
She's now experiencing
complete muscular paralysis.

208
00:12:08,089 --> 00:12:11,189
She's got three minutes
to breathe or she'll suffocate.

209
00:12:11,389 --> 00:12:13,189
So now we intubate.

210
00:12:13,789 --> 00:12:15,989
Taking a laryngoscope like so.

211
00:12:16,289 --> 00:12:18,189
Hold her head
in an extended position.

212
00:12:18,389 --> 00:12:21,889
Enter laterally, put up
the base of the tongue, up and out...

213
00:12:22,089 --> 00:12:23,689
...visualizing the trachea.

214
00:12:23,889 --> 00:12:26,289
There it is, fellas. Take a look.

215
00:12:26,889 --> 00:12:28,789
You see it?
lt's right over there.

216
00:12:30,389 --> 00:12:32,189
Come on, guys!

217
00:12:32,389 --> 00:12:35,789
Take our tube and enter here.

218
00:12:37,389 --> 00:12:40,589
ln the middle of surgery,
l'll switch over to the telothane.

219
00:12:42,289 --> 00:12:43,689
Stirrups up?

220
00:12:46,189 --> 00:12:47,689
How is John?

221
00:12:47,889 --> 00:12:51,489
His fever broke today.
He'll go back to school tomorrow.

222
00:12:51,689 --> 00:12:53,589
Now we can check
the pupillary reflexes.

223
00:12:53,789 --> 00:12:57,289
Though she's unconscious,
the pupils should react to light...

224
00:12:57,489 --> 00:12:59,889
...and let us know
that the old brain is okay.

225
00:13:00,089 --> 00:13:04,888
That's it. Anesthesia's the easiest job
in the world until something goes wrong.

226
00:13:05,088 --> 00:13:08,488
lt's 99% boredom
and 1 % scared-shitless panic...

227
00:13:08,788 --> 00:13:12,888
...which we try to avoid.
The patient's yours, Dr. Richards.

228
00:13:13,088 --> 00:13:14,788
lf you move in behind me...

229
00:13:14,988 --> 00:13:18,188
...you'll see what l am going to do
for this young woman.

230
00:13:18,388 --> 00:13:19,388
Some music, please.

231
00:13:22,088 --> 00:13:25,988
Actually, what l'm going to do
is get her out of a hell of a mess.

232
00:13:26,688 --> 00:13:27,988
She's pregnant.

233
00:13:28,188 --> 00:13:30,588
She doesn't want her husband to know.

234
00:13:31,788 --> 00:13:33,888
lt's none of my business.

235
00:13:34,388 --> 00:13:37,288
l'm just her surgeon.
l don't run her life.

236
00:13:39,488 --> 00:13:42,088
So in fact, our task is simplified...

237
00:13:42,288 --> 00:13:44,988
...when the uterus is
anteverted and anteflexed.

238
00:13:45,188 --> 00:13:49,088
This is a function of the muscular
attachments, of which there are five.

239
00:13:49,288 --> 00:13:50,388
You should know them.

240
00:13:51,288 --> 00:13:55,088
They're the broad ligaments,
the round and cardinal ligaments...

241
00:13:55,288 --> 00:13:58,688
...and the endopelvic fascia,
the uterosacral ligaments.

242
00:14:04,288 --> 00:14:05,288
Something wrong?

243
00:14:06,588 --> 00:14:09,587
She just threw a PVC,
and her blood pressure's falling.

244
00:14:10,287 --> 00:14:11,987
l got 90 over 60.

245
00:14:12,187 --> 00:14:15,287
She's fully oxygenated.
Red as a cherry down here.

246
00:14:15,487 --> 00:14:17,687
How much longer you got?

247
00:14:19,087 --> 00:14:20,487
Just a couple of minutes.

248
00:14:20,687 --> 00:14:23,187
l don't like this.
Her blood pressure is still falling.

249
00:14:25,487 --> 00:14:26,387
Damn!

250
00:14:26,587 --> 00:14:30,287
We should stop. She may be getting
too much vagal stimulation.

251
00:14:30,587 --> 00:14:31,887
Jesus Christ.

252
00:14:32,187 --> 00:14:32,987
What's the matter?

253
00:14:33,187 --> 00:14:35,487
l don't know.
Nothing's the matter!

254
00:14:35,687 --> 00:14:37,887
Something's the matter.
She's going to arrest!

255
00:14:38,087 --> 00:14:38,987
l can't find anything!

256
00:14:56,087 --> 00:14:58,887
l get a 1 00 over 80.
Her pressure's climbing.

257
00:14:59,087 --> 00:15:02,787
Let's finish up. l'd like to get
this mother off the table.

258
00:15:05,287 --> 00:15:07,087
Sponge, please.

259
00:15:10,087 --> 00:15:13,587
One-twenty over 80 and climbing.
She's okay.

260
00:15:15,386 --> 00:15:19,086
-These tissues can go to pathology.
-Can l start bringing her out?

261
00:15:19,286 --> 00:15:20,786
Yeah, bring her out, Jim.

262
00:15:25,786 --> 00:15:28,886
Okay, Mrs. Greenly,
it's time to wake up.

263
00:15:29,186 --> 00:15:30,586
Okay, Nancy?

264
00:15:30,786 --> 00:15:33,486
Mrs. Greenly? Wake up.

265
00:15:33,886 --> 00:15:36,686
Nance, can you give me
a cough, please?

266
00:15:51,286 --> 00:15:55,586
Jesus Christ!
Her pupils are fixed and dilated.

267
00:15:56,586 --> 00:15:59,086
The pupils, they're fixed.

268
00:15:59,686 --> 00:16:01,186
Dilated.

269
00:16:05,286 --> 00:16:07,386
Oh, my God!

270
00:16:08,286 --> 00:16:11,786
Pre-op diagnosis,
acute gastric ulceration.

271
00:16:11,986 --> 00:16:14,386
Post-op diagnosis, the same.

272
00:16:14,886 --> 00:16:17,486
Surgeon, Dr. Wilson.

273
00:16:19,886 --> 00:16:22,885
-Where's Schwartz? Cholecystectomy?
-Bed three.

274
00:16:25,485 --> 00:16:29,385
-Mr. Schwartz, l'm Dr. Bellows.
-You don't got to talk so loud.

275
00:16:29,585 --> 00:16:30,785
How you feel?

276
00:16:30,985 --> 00:16:32,085
Just ''eh''?

277
00:16:32,285 --> 00:16:34,885
You want to get on your side
for me, please?

278
00:16:35,085 --> 00:16:37,785
-On your side.
-Speak up, l can't hear you.

279
00:16:37,985 --> 00:16:40,585
What'd they give you
in that operating room?

280
00:16:40,785 --> 00:16:42,085
Do you have any pain?

281
00:16:42,285 --> 00:16:45,585
lf l had any pain,
l would go see a doctor.

282
00:16:45,985 --> 00:16:48,585
Now you want to breathe
for me real easy?

283
00:16:50,185 --> 00:16:52,185
That's it. Slowly.

284
00:16:52,585 --> 00:16:55,785
She was given narceine
to rule out pre-op narcotic....

285
00:16:57,185 --> 00:16:58,085
Easy!

286
00:16:58,285 --> 00:17:01,185
Two units without effect,
a few peripheral fasciculations.

287
00:17:01,385 --> 00:17:03,085
So it's not succinylcholine?

288
00:17:04,985 --> 00:17:07,485
Delayed return of consciousness
of cryptogenic origin.

289
00:17:10,185 --> 00:17:13,585
l see no reason not to transfer her
to the intensive care unit.

290
00:17:13,785 --> 00:17:16,085
Mr. Schwartz, you're going to be fine.

291
00:17:16,285 --> 00:17:17,985
That's what you think!

292
00:17:20,885 --> 00:17:24,785
-A grim prognosis, to say the least.
-Rather tragic.

293
00:17:25,085 --> 00:17:26,884
Someone should notify Dr. George.

294
00:17:27,084 --> 00:17:29,384
He'll want to review
the anesthetic protocol.

295
00:17:29,584 --> 00:17:31,584
Right, he's been paged.

296
00:17:31,784 --> 00:17:33,884
Looks like
another anesthetic reaction.

297
00:17:35,984 --> 00:17:38,984
Page Dr. Bendix.
4-4-4-3-2.

298
00:17:39,184 --> 00:17:40,084
Check.

299
00:17:40,284 --> 00:17:42,184
George is not here.

300
00:17:42,384 --> 00:17:45,484
No, Dr. Bendix. Bendix!

301
00:17:45,684 --> 00:17:48,384
Maybe he left the hospital.
Try his office.

302
00:17:49,584 --> 00:17:51,984
Could you page Dr. Wheeler, please?

303
00:17:52,184 --> 00:17:55,484
So you see, Jimmy,
your kidneys are sick.

304
00:17:55,684 --> 00:17:56,884
They don't work right.

305
00:17:57,084 --> 00:18:00,584
We need to take out the sick kidneys
and put in a new one.

306
00:18:00,784 --> 00:18:01,684
Today?

307
00:18:02,084 --> 00:18:04,784
No, not today.
We have to wait until...

308
00:18:04,984 --> 00:18:07,084
...there's a kidney we can put in.

309
00:18:07,284 --> 00:18:08,184
Tomorrow?

310
00:18:08,684 --> 00:18:11,684
l don't know when.
But it could be a while.

311
00:18:13,284 --> 00:18:16,584
<i>Dr. Wheeler, call extension 3-5-6.</i>

312
00:18:16,784 --> 00:18:19,784
You can have one of these.
Which color do you like?

313
00:18:21,884 --> 00:18:22,684
Purple.

314
00:18:23,284 --> 00:18:24,284
Take two.

315
00:18:24,584 --> 00:18:26,384
l like purple.

316
00:18:26,884 --> 00:18:28,884
l can see that.

317
00:18:33,783 --> 00:18:35,283
l like red too.

318
00:18:36,683 --> 00:18:38,383
Dr. Wheeler.

319
00:18:49,983 --> 00:18:53,383
Excuse me, l have to go
to intensive care now.

320
00:18:53,583 --> 00:18:55,383
A nurse should be right in.

321
00:18:57,083 --> 00:18:58,883
Surgical lCU.

322
00:19:06,983 --> 00:19:08,483
What's her status?

323
00:19:08,783 --> 00:19:09,783
Greenly?

324
00:19:09,983 --> 00:19:11,983
Complete squash rot.

325
00:19:12,183 --> 00:19:13,783
She's a total Gomer.

326
00:19:14,883 --> 00:19:16,183
lt's brain death.

327
00:19:28,983 --> 00:19:32,983
That patient was transferred
to the Jefferson lnstitute yesterday.

328
00:20:09,182 --> 00:20:11,182
How can this happen?

329
00:20:12,082 --> 00:20:13,382
All this....

330
00:20:21,682 --> 00:20:23,582
Did you do an EEG?

331
00:20:24,282 --> 00:20:25,182
Flat.

332
00:20:25,982 --> 00:20:27,682
Completely flat?

333
00:20:28,082 --> 00:20:29,782
Completely flat.

334
00:20:30,782 --> 00:20:32,282
Did you repeat it?

335
00:20:32,582 --> 00:20:33,982
No, not yet.

336
00:20:35,482 --> 00:20:37,482
What happened during the D and C?

337
00:20:37,782 --> 00:20:38,582
Nothing.

338
00:20:38,782 --> 00:20:41,682
lt's an unremarkable case,
according to the notes.

339
00:20:42,082 --> 00:20:44,082
Transient PVCs late in the operation.

340
00:20:44,581 --> 00:20:45,981
Nothing else.

341
00:20:46,381 --> 00:20:47,481
She never woke up?

342
00:20:51,581 --> 00:20:53,281
l want to look at her chart.

343
00:21:07,581 --> 00:21:10,781
lf it were my friend,
l don't know if l'd be that cool.

344
00:21:14,781 --> 00:21:16,481
The potassium was what?

345
00:21:16,881 --> 00:21:18,881
One-eight? Are you sure?

346
00:21:19,081 --> 00:21:20,881
lt must be a mistake.

347
00:21:22,781 --> 00:21:24,181
Honey, l'm sorry.

348
00:21:24,381 --> 00:21:26,481
l know you two were really close.

349
00:21:29,381 --> 00:21:30,481
Susan?

350
00:21:37,081 --> 00:21:39,981
There doesn't seem to be
anything unusual in the chart.

351
00:21:40,181 --> 00:21:43,581
Normal 28-year-old patient
in good health for a D and C...

352
00:21:43,881 --> 00:21:47,481
...underwent telothane anesthesia,
comes out in irreversible coma.

353
00:21:48,581 --> 00:21:51,580
lt's well-documented
that telothane causes liver damage...

354
00:21:51,880 --> 00:21:55,280
...and severe side effects in
a small percentage of surgical cases.

355
00:21:55,480 --> 00:21:59,380
-That's just the risk of anesthesia.
-l know you're upset.

356
00:22:00,080 --> 00:22:01,680
l'm not upset.

357
00:22:02,780 --> 00:22:06,680
You think because l'm a woman,
l'm going to be upset. l'm fine.

358
00:22:07,580 --> 00:22:11,080
l want to understand the variables
as they apply to this patient.

359
00:22:11,280 --> 00:22:13,080
l'm sure you agree that's indicated.

360
00:22:13,280 --> 00:22:14,180
''This patient''?

361
00:22:14,380 --> 00:22:17,180
Here we have an ordinary,
uninteresting case...

362
00:22:17,380 --> 00:22:21,980
...of surgical reaction to telothane
anesthesia in a healthy patient.

363
00:22:22,180 --> 00:22:25,080
As far as l can tell,
there are no unusual aspects...

364
00:22:25,280 --> 00:22:28,380
...except that the patient
was tissue-typed.

365
00:22:28,580 --> 00:22:29,780
Tissue-typed for D and C?

366
00:22:31,180 --> 00:22:32,980
There's got to be some mistake.

367
00:22:33,180 --> 00:22:36,980
Here it is. No name on the slip
and no billing number.

368
00:22:38,580 --> 00:22:42,280
That's not the first time the lab
ran a test on the wrong patient.

369
00:22:46,280 --> 00:22:49,580
Let's go home.
l think you're tired.

370
00:22:50,380 --> 00:22:53,580
l think l'd better check
the tissue-typing lab.

371
00:22:55,180 --> 00:22:55,980
Why?

372
00:22:59,579 --> 00:23:02,979
Nancy's problem was not caused
by wrong lab tests.

373
00:23:05,079 --> 00:23:06,179
l know.

374
00:23:06,379 --> 00:23:08,479
Honey, you're grabbing at straws.

375
00:23:09,579 --> 00:23:11,179
Let's go have some dinner.

376
00:23:11,379 --> 00:23:13,379
-l'm not hungry.
-We'll check the lab later.

377
00:23:13,579 --> 00:23:16,579
Stop acting as if
there's something wrong with me...

378
00:23:16,779 --> 00:23:19,679
...or the way l'm thinking!
l'm checking the lab now.

379
00:23:19,879 --> 00:23:20,679
They're closed.

380
00:23:20,879 --> 00:23:22,579
l won't just stand here!

381
00:23:22,979 --> 00:23:25,179
Susan, the lab is closed.

382
00:23:25,379 --> 00:23:27,379
lt closed at six 6:00.

383
00:23:30,579 --> 00:23:31,579
ls she all right?

384
00:23:33,079 --> 00:23:35,679
Yeah, she just....

385
00:23:36,679 --> 00:23:38,479
She likes to do things
her own way.

386
00:23:48,779 --> 00:23:49,679
Who's that?

387
00:23:50,679 --> 00:23:51,579
Dr. Wheeler.

388
00:23:51,779 --> 00:23:53,379
We're closed.

389
00:23:53,579 --> 00:23:56,579
We don't do any determinations
after six, doctor.

390
00:23:56,779 --> 00:23:59,179
l want to look at
your requisition book.

391
00:23:59,679 --> 00:24:03,078
What does it mean when there's
no name and number on the slip?

392
00:24:03,478 --> 00:24:04,778
There's....

393
00:24:05,378 --> 00:24:08,378
There's always
a name or a number, doctor.

394
00:24:08,578 --> 00:24:11,578
For example, Nancy Greenly.
You did tissue-typing...

395
00:24:11,778 --> 00:24:14,078
...but there's no physician name
and billing number.

396
00:24:14,278 --> 00:24:15,678
Let me see.

397
00:24:19,378 --> 00:24:22,078
Yes, you see, it's been
printed out by computer.

398
00:24:22,478 --> 00:24:24,078
That's hospital policy.

399
00:24:24,278 --> 00:24:28,278
A certain number of these tests
are randomly ordered by computer...

400
00:24:28,578 --> 00:24:29,778
...as a quality check.

401
00:24:29,978 --> 00:24:31,978
We do the tests here,
they're sent out...

402
00:24:32,178 --> 00:24:34,078
...and done again by an outside lab.

403
00:24:34,278 --> 00:24:36,578
The computer ordered
this test on Greenly?

404
00:24:37,478 --> 00:24:39,578
Yeah, central computer.

405
00:24:40,078 --> 00:24:41,778
Why don't you just show me?

406
00:24:41,978 --> 00:24:43,278
-l can't.
-Why not?

407
00:24:43,678 --> 00:24:44,978
l'm not supposed to.

408
00:24:45,178 --> 00:24:46,678
lt's really important.

409
00:24:48,378 --> 00:24:50,778
Anyway, that information
isn't coded.

410
00:24:50,978 --> 00:24:52,978
lf it isn't coded,
l can't pull it out.

411
00:24:53,578 --> 00:24:54,978
l mean, who would want it?

412
00:24:55,178 --> 00:24:58,478
Well, let's say l wanted a list
of all the patients...

413
00:24:58,678 --> 00:25:00,578
...who had tissue-typing
in the last month.

414
00:25:00,778 --> 00:25:02,078
Same thing. Not coded.

415
00:25:02,278 --> 00:25:04,778
What do you do?
What good is all this equipment?

416
00:25:05,078 --> 00:25:06,478
l thought you recorded information.

417
00:25:06,778 --> 00:25:11,077
We do, but the truth is, we install
these computers to bill patients.

418
00:25:11,377 --> 00:25:14,177
We code patient name and number,
medical or surgical...

419
00:25:14,377 --> 00:25:17,877
...admission diagnosis,
therapy and discharge diagnosis.

420
00:25:18,077 --> 00:25:19,877
Okay, wait a minute.

421
00:25:20,077 --> 00:25:23,377
Can you give me a list
of all surgical patients...

422
00:25:23,577 --> 00:25:25,777
...with discharge diagnoses of coma?

423
00:25:40,677 --> 00:25:42,577
Okay, we have...

424
00:25:42,877 --> 00:25:45,577
...one general category
under ''coma'' ...

425
00:25:45,977 --> 00:25:49,177
...and nine subcategories
under ''brain syndromes.''

426
00:25:49,377 --> 00:25:50,377
Good.

427
00:25:50,577 --> 00:25:53,477
l want a list
of all surgical patients...

428
00:25:53,677 --> 00:25:56,677
...with general category
of coma in the past year.

429
00:25:58,877 --> 00:25:59,977
You're sure you want it?

430
00:26:11,077 --> 00:26:12,577
l had no idea.

431
00:26:12,777 --> 00:26:14,477
lt's a big hospital.

432
00:26:15,276 --> 00:26:17,076
Are you married or what?

433
00:26:19,576 --> 00:26:20,976
Thank you.

434
00:26:42,976 --> 00:26:45,876
Surgical lCU. That's right.

435
00:27:16,376 --> 00:27:17,876
Where'd you get this?

436
00:27:19,876 --> 00:27:23,275
lt's against the law.
lt's illegal to tap a data bank.

437
00:27:23,475 --> 00:27:24,775
l don't see why.
l'm a doctor.

438
00:27:24,975 --> 00:27:27,575
-l've got research--
-That's not the point!

439
00:27:27,775 --> 00:27:31,175
Every officer got the lecture.
No access without authorization.

440
00:27:31,375 --> 00:27:33,175
-They can throw you out.
-Never mind that.

441
00:27:33,375 --> 00:27:34,475
''Never mind''?

442
00:27:36,275 --> 00:27:37,575
Look at this.

443
00:27:37,975 --> 00:27:39,575
Two hundred and forty names.

444
00:27:39,775 --> 00:27:43,075
Ten are young people
admitted for minor procedures.

445
00:27:43,275 --> 00:27:45,975
Breast biopsy, appendectomy.

446
00:27:46,175 --> 00:27:49,175
They all come out in a coma.
Aren't you surprised?

447
00:27:49,775 --> 00:27:53,675
The risk of surgical anesthesia
is six per 1 00,000.

448
00:27:53,875 --> 00:27:57,475
ln a hospital this size, 1 0 patients
